content: The new update with audio alerts is AMAZING!!... I turn it on... and as soon as I put my bag down (4 sec delay), it shouts the distance to the green!!... I don't even need to take my phone out of my bag!! Beautiful!!... the only con, is it has some trouble transiting from one hole to the next.  I put my bag down on the tee box and it reads out the distance to the previous hole.  Maybe have it transfer over once it's inside 50 yrds? Or maybe have it track the tee boxes in the background and when it gets inside of 20 yrds, to transfer to the next hole... small annoyance, but other then that, fantastic app and I love the update!!
replyContent: Thanks for the feedback! The hole should advance when you get within 35 yards of the center of the green.  It could be that your phone is not getting close enough if you are leaving it in your bag instead of your pocket while you putt.

I compared the distances provided by this app side by side with my SkyCaddie (before I sold it on eBay) and they were identical in most cases.  I can stand on fairway yardage markers and be within a yard. I've found that I can leave the app running (change setting to "always on") and my battery makes it through the entire round.  Just switch off the screen between shots and have your car charger ready for the ride home from the course. One course I wanted to play wasn't in the database, so I visited the developer's site and mapped it myself in about fifteen minutes.  The online mapping tool is awesome, but nearly all courses are mapped now.   I've also asked a question of the developer and he provided a detailed response in less than 24-hours.  That's impressive for a $2 app!

replyContent: If you are seeing "- - -" instead of a distance it means the app thinks your are more than 999 yards away from the green. That can happen if you are testing from home, or if your phone isn't getting an updated GPS signal. Another cause could be a problem with the course mapping. Check your mappings on skydroid.net. Use a GPS test app for GPS issues

replyContent: The 2 things that can cause yardage inaccuracies are: 1) bad GPS location and 2) bad course mapping. Looks like you've encountered both issues. When the markers were off in the woods, that was a bad course mapping. These are rare and get removed/corrected quickly. Bad GPS signal, is like a bad cell signal, can happen randomly, not much we can do.

content: This is a great app and I love that it features both small and large golf courses. However, after several updates, it now has a problem. After about eight holes, it gets stuck on a distance -- unfortunately incorrect -- and won't change. Only way to proceed is to shut the app down and restart it.  This needs to be fixed or I will have to look around for another GPS program. Another plus of SkyDroid is that almost every course I have played has been available to download. The download is free and fast. If a course is not available, you can go to the SkyDroid Web site and map the course yourself. The site provides a quick, simple, clear tutorial.   Recently, SkyDroid added a scoring feature. It has some good things about it (allows you to keep track of putts and fairways hit) but, as far as I can tell, you can't export the resulting scorecard; it is stuck inside the SkyDroid app. So I use another app called Easy Scorecard that allows me to email a .jpg of my scorecard at the end of the round.

replyContent: Sorry to hear it. We've never had that issue ourselves or from anyone else. I strongly suspect it's an issue with your phone's hardware and the GPS chip. Try an app like "GPS Test" to diagnose (test while outdoors) and if you confirm the issue consider seeing if you can get the phone exchanged for a new one (hopefully for free).

replyContent: Jeffrey, sometimes the phone will take a bit of time to get a good GPS lock when you first start using it. Make sure you are outdoors if you test it somewhere. Sometimes powering down and restarting the phone clears GPS issues. Email us at contact@skydroid.net for additional help.

This is a fantastic app which I have downloaded just an hour ago.  My local course wasn't available for download so I used the app to navigate to my course. All this was completed in 20 minutes and is dead easy to accomplish.  Anyone who knows the layout of a course can do it too. In the past when I mapped a course myself using SkyCaddie I had to be physically on the course to record Front, Middle, Back of every green which took usually 3-4 hours including trip to the course the best part of a day was gone.  After which I had to upload it to the internet site, get it verified and wait until it was put onto their servers which could take a month or two. I couldn't believe it when I installed the app I checked to see if my local course was there and it was.  After downloading course I went to the course which is nearby.
